Unchanged Impact to our thesis
Modest upside Financial results versus consensus
Modest revision lower Direction of next 12- month consensus EPS
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

Delivery Hero had already refined its guidance for 2025 yesterday after market close (see our report here) trimming adj. EBITDA and FCF due to fx headwinds. The company had also published its Group adj. EBITDA for H1, which came in \(7\%\) ahead of consensus. This morning the company provided the full colour from the release, with GMV in- line with consensus, revenues \(2\%\) ahead in H1 (or \(4\%\) for Q2), and trends in its core Asia business saw GMV in- line with consensus but generated an \(11\%\) beat on adj. EBITDA to consensus for that region. With a key focus remaining on performance in South Korea, we think the Group performance in H1 will be received reasonably well by investors. Operating leverage is also being seen, with marketing and G&A flat on an underlying basis year on year. Saudi order volumes grew \(>20\%\) YoY in Q2, which will alleviate some concern on the competition impact there and is a positive read- across for talabat. However, some of the contingent liabilities are now being paid in H2 - see below - which may be discussed on the earnings call.

Contingent liabilities are in the €562- 923m range, mostly related to Spain (Glovo), broadly as expected. More importantly, in July, Glovo began receiving final reclassification decisions from local authorities requesting the payment of some liabilities and, as of July 31, had requested €450m payment (within the contingency range given here). Glovo will not recognize the reclassifications, but rather keeps the possibility to continue defending the self- employed status through all available instances by meeting the payment requests in the second half of 2025".
MORGAN STANLEY & CO. INTERNATIONAL PLC+
Constantin P Kollmann
Delivery Hero SE (DHER.DE, DHER.GY)

Our sum- of- the- parts values (i) talabat in line with the fair value implied by our price target, (ii) South Korea at 9x EBITDA on 2025 (which equates to a cyclical- low multiple for a food delivery company given competition is intense), and (iii) assume leaves the remaining business as optionality i.e. zero value. We consider 2024 net debt, provisions and assume €0.6bn of contingent liabilities are paid. We factor in a \(20\%\) conglomerate discount.
talabat outperforms expectations Competition eases in South Korea and Saudi Group FCF generation and cash conversion improves above expectations Resolution on Spanish contingencies/fines
Rising competition in South Korea/MENA, delaying margin expansion Competition intensifying in core markets/regions Group FCF dynamics remain compressed Slowing macro environment

We value talabat on an average of (1) a DCF and (2) FCF yield. (1) Our DCF uses a \(10\%\) WACC, \(3.5\%\) terminal growth, \(12\%\) 10- year revenue CAGR and \(8.9\%\) EBITDA to GMV margin. (2) Our FCF yield is \(3.8\%\) on 2025e, equivalent to Jahez's 2- year average FCF yield which, although it is in line, factors in talabat trading at a \(25\%\) premium on fundamentals, but discounting back \(25\%\) to adjust for Jahez being Saudi listed, i.e. factoring in a \(25\%\) 'Saudi premium'.
Faster TAM growth Higher market share Faster scaling of grocery Lower competitor intensity
